{"timestamp": "2025-12-01 16:42:14.806418", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — multi‑tier Clos EBGP lab\n\nScope and goal\n- Assess current network health, detect anomalies, localize any faulty devices, and identify likely root causes based on the available runtime data (interface addressing, routing table, BGP view, and host reachability).\n- Collected data: host/interface IPs, kernel routes, FRR BGP route tables (per router), and end‑to‑end pings.\n\nExecutive summary (short)\n- The network is converged and operational. Both hosts (pc_0_0 and pc_0_1) are reachable to each other with no packet loss and low latency.\n- FRR BGP on super‑spine, spines and leaves is established and propagating the leaf /24 host networks. Routes for 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 are present in BGP tables across routers with expected AS‑paths.\n- No interface DOWN states, no kernel route inconsistencies, and no packet loss observed in host pings. No evidence of an active fault from the collected information.\n\nCollected evidence (key findings)\n1) Host reachability\n- get_reachability summary: pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0: 4/4 pings received, 0% loss, avg RTT ≈ 2.99 ms.\n- Direct ping from pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1: 4/4, 0% loss, avg RTT ≈ 2.72 ms.\n  - Ping output: 4 transmitted, 4 received, rtt min/avg/max/mdev = 1.732/2.718/3.154/0.573 ms\n- Conclusion: ICMP connectivity between hosts is healthy and symmetric (no packet loss).\n\n2) Interface and IP state (aggregated)\n- All router interfaces involved in the topology are UP and have the expected /31 or /24 addresses:\n  - super_spine_router_0: eth0 172.16.0.0/31 (to spine_router_0_0), eth1 172.16.0.2/31 (to spine_router_0_1)\n  - spine_router_0_0: eth0 172.16.0.1/31 (to super), eth1 172.16.0.4/31 (to leaf_0_0), eth2 172.16.0.6/31 (to leaf_0_1)\n  - spine_router_0_1: eth0 172.16.0.3/31 (to super), eth1 172.16.0.8/31 (to leaf_0_0), eth2 172.16.0.10/31 (to leaf_0_1)\n  - leaf_router_0_0: eth0 172.16.0.5/31 (to spine_0_0), eth1 172.16.0.9/31 (to spine_0_1), eth2 10.0.0.1/24 (to pc_0_0)\n  - leaf_router_0_1: eth0 172.16.0.7/31 (to spine_0_0), eth1 172.16.0.11/31 (to spine_0_1), eth2 10.0.1.1/24 (to pc_0_1)\n- No RX/TX errors shown in interfaces outputs; all logical links are UP.\n\n3) Kernel routes (examples)\n- leaf_router_0_0:\n  - 10.0.0.0/24 directly connected via eth2 (src 10.0.0.1)\n  - 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.4 (next-hop = spine_router_0_0)\n- leaf_router_0_1:\n  - 10.0.1.0/24 directly connected via eth2 (src 10.0.1.1)\n  - 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.6 (next-hop = spine_router_0_0)\n- spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1 have kernel route entries for /31 links and BGP‑installed next hops for the two leaf /24s.\n\n4) BGP status / route propagation (per router extracts)\n- super_spine_router_0 (local AS 65000)\n  - Shows both 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 learned via two paths (spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1). Best paths selected via 172.16.0.1 (spine_0_0).\n- spine_router_0_0 (local AS 65100)\n  - Has installed 10.0.0.0/24 via leaf_router_0_0 (172.16.0.5) and 10.0.1.0/24 via leaf_router_0_1 (172.16.0.7).\n- spine_router_0_1 (local AS 65101)\n  - Has installed 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.9 and 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.11 (leaf attachments).\n- leaf_router_0_0 (local AS 65200)\n  - BGP table: 10.0.0.0/24 is locally originated (next-hop 0.0.0.0 / connected); has paths to 10.0.1/24 via spines.\n- leaf_router_0_1 (local AS 65201)\n  - BGP table: 10.0.1/24 locally originated; has paths to 10.0.0/24 via spines.\n- AS‑path propagation seen is consistent with design: leaf ASes advertise their local /24, spines learn them, and super‑spine receives routes from both spines.\n\nBehavioral observations and interpretation\n- Convergence: BGP appears converged. Each leaf advertises its /24 locally; spines learn leaf prefixes and advertise them to super‑spine; super‑spine sees multiple best/candidate paths and has selected a best next‑hop. The BGP AS path values align with the designed AS numbers (leaf ASes 65200/65201, spine ASes 65100/65101, super‑spine AS 65000).\n- Forwarding: Kernel routes on routers show BGP‑installed routes with valid next hops that match the topology. End‑to‑end forwarding (pc_0_0 <-> pc_0_1) works with minimal latency (~2–3 ms).\n- Symmetry/asymmetry: Multiple valid BGP paths exist across the fabric (super‑spine sees two paths for each prefix). BGP path selection differs per router (expected) and leads to asymmetric next hops in some cases. This is normal in EBGP multi‑path topologies and is not a fault by itself.\n\nAnomalies (none detected)\n- No packet loss observed between hosts.\n- No interface down or error counters in ifconfig outputs.\n- BGP tables show expected prefixes and AS paths for all routers; no missing prefixes for the two /24 host networks.\n- No evidence of route flapping, suppressed/damped prefixes, or RIB/FIB inconsistencies in the collected FRR outputs.\n\nDevice localization (where any problems would appear)\n- Based on the collected info, there are no faulty devices to localize; all routers (super_spine_router_0, spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1, leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1) are present, have their links UP, and carry expected BGP routes.\n- If problems were to appear, relevant places to check (from most to least local) would be:\n  1. leaf router connecting the affected host (eth2) — local advertisement of the /24\n  2. spine(s) attached to that leaf — next‑hop and AS path propagation\n  3. super‑spine — aggregation and selection\n  4. interface link counters between those specific routers (the /31 links)\n\nRoot cause determination\n- There is no root cause to identify for a failure because no functional anomaly was found. Observed state is consistent with a healthy EBGP Clos/fat‑tree:\n  - BGP sessions established and prefixes exchanged along expected AS‑path chains.\n  - Kernel routes and BGP selected routes are correct and consistent with the topology.\n  - Host ICMP confirms successful forwarding.\n\nAdditional notes (observations that may be relevant later)\n- Multiple candidate paths appear in BGP tables (expected). If a policy of strict symmetry is required, this is an operational consideration (not a fault).\n- The super‑spine selected spine_router_0_0 for best path to both prefixes at the time of capture; this is a normal result of BGP selection criteria and local pref/AS path differences.\n- No FRR process status was checked (systemctl) and no deep logs were gathered; current checks focused on control plane and forwarding state.\n\nConclusion\n- Network health: OK / converged.\n- Anomalies: None detected with the provided data.\n- Faulty devices: None identified.\n- Root cause: N/A (no failure present).\n\nIf you want, I can:\n- Collect BGP neighbor/session details (show ip bgp summary / neighbors) and FRR running configs for a deeper control‑plane verification.\n- Retrieve interface counters over time or examine FRR logs for historical flaps if you suspect transient issues. (These actions would be investigative only; no mitigation will be applied unless you request it.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 12951, "output_tokens": 4068, "total_tokens": 17019, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 11904}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1984}}}
